/PL779/XX/PR

/KAJEWS AROUND THE WORLD/PR

Who Are These Jews?/XX/PR

There were women who sat in the market/PR

selling beets and cabbages so their men could study;/PR

they were Jews./PR

/PR

There were men of Yemen, great swordsmen,/PR

guards of the king: they were Jews./PR

/PR

There are dark women from India, wearing saris,/PR

Black farmers from Ethiopia,/PR

Children with slanted eyes: all Jews./PR

/PR

There are dressmakers and sculptors,/PR

thieves and philanthropists, scholars and nurses/PR

beggars and generals./PR

/PR

There are women who follow every rule of Kashrut/PR

and men who know none of the rules,/PR

yet all of us are Jews./PR

/PR

Though we are not alike in mind or body,/PR

somewhere in the depths of our souls/PR

we know we are the children of one people./PR

/PR

We share a history, a hope, and some prayers;/PR

We speak many languages;/PR

We have heard one Voice:/PR

/PR

All of us stood together at Sinai/PR

When our past and our future/PR

Exploded in thunder and flame before us./PR

Ruth Brin/XX/PR

/PR

