/KAA Blessing/XX/PR

/IT(For birth, bar/bat mitzvah)/PR

/PR

May your eyes sparkle with the light of Torah,/PR

and your ears hear the music of its words./PR

May the space between each letter of the scrolls/PR

bring warmth and comfort to your soul./PR

May the syllables draw holiness from your heart,/PR

and may this holiness be gentle and soothing/PR

to the world./PR

May your study be passionate,/PR

and meanings bear more meanings/PR

until Life itself arrays itself to you/PR

as a dazzling wedding feast./PR

And may your conversation,/PR

even of the commonplace,/PR

be a blessing to all who listen to your words/PR

and see the Torah glowing on your face./PR

Danny Siegel (Inspired by Talmud Berah/±ot 17A)/XX/PR

/PR

/IT(For bar/bat mitzvah)/PR

/PR

The days come and go. Imperceptibly our lives change. We
grow older and are hardly aware of it. Our children grow up
and we hardly notice. Then, suddenly, we come to this time and
we realize that our sons and daughters are children no longer.
They have become young men and women, ready to take their
first step into adulthood./PR

/PR

We are grateful that we have been able to bring them this far.
We are thankful for the strength to cope with the stresses and
responsibilities of rearing them. And we give thanks for the
pleasure and pride we have had in them./PI/PR

/PR

/PR

/PR

/PGREADINGS: LIFE CYCLE/XX786/XX/PR

Now we realize they are children no longer. Only another year,
two, three, and they will begin to go from our homes to find
their own way in the world./PR

/PR

We ask ourselves, have we truly prepared them for this? Have
we done enough, taught them enough? We are almost afraid to
let them go./PR

/PR

Yet it was for this that we raised them, that they might grow
up to take their places in the world./PR

/IT(For aufruf, engagement, anniversary)/PR

/PR

/PR

We are thankful for  and /PR

and for what they mean and bring to each other./PR

We are thankful that a deep need for each other,/PR

and the capacity to love and to care for one another/PR

has been implanted within them./PR

May they be modest in their demands of one another,/PR

and generous in their giving to each other./PR

May they never measure how much love or encouragement they
offer;/PR

may they never count the times they forgive./PR

Rather, may they always be grateful/PR

that they have one another/PR

and that they are able to express their love/PR

in acts of kindness./PR

Keep them gentle in their speech./PR

When they offer words of criticism,/PR

may they be chosen with care, and spoken softly./PR

May they waste no opportunity to speak words of sympathy,/PR

of appreciation, of praise./PR

May they be blessed with health, happiness and contentment./PR

Above all, may they be granted the wisdom to build a/PR

joyous and peaceful home./PR

Sidney Greenberg (adapted)/XX/PR

