/PL793/XXREADINGS: PRELUDES TO KADDISH/XX/PR

/KAFrom My Motheròs Home/XX/PR

My motheròs mother died/PR

In the spring of her days./PR

And her daughter/PR

Did not remember her face./PR

Her portrait, engraved/PR

Upon my grandfatheròs heart,/PR

Was erased from the world of images/PR

After his death./PR

Only her mirror remained in the home,/PR

Sunken with age into the silver frame./PR

And I, her pale granddaughter, who does not resemble her,/PR

Look into it today as into/PR

A pool which conceals its treasures/PR

Beneath the waters./PR

Very deep down, behind my face,/PR

I see a young woman/PR

Pink-cheeked, smiling./PR

And a wig on her head./PR

She puts/PR

An elongated earring on her ear-lobe, threading it/PR

Through a tiny hole in the dainty flesh/PR

Of her ear./PR

Very deep down, behind my face, the bright goldness/PR

of her eyes sends out rays,/PR

And the mirror carries on the tradition of/PR

The family: That she was very beautiful./PR

Leah Goldberg (translated by Ezra Spicehandler)/XX/PR

